04038nam a22005055i 9780300171716DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20112011ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001717167 a10.12987/97803001717162doi  a(DE-B1597)485709  a(OCoLC)709605936  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aE280.B36 -- S33 2011eb 7aBIO0060002bisacsh04a973.3/86092aB1 aSchaeper, Thomas J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEdward Bancroft :bScientist, Author, Spy /cThomas J. Schaeper. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Early Life -- t2. On the Rise in London -- t3. Initiation in Covert Activity -- t4. First Steps -- t5. Our Man in Paris -- t6. The Franco-American Alliance -- t7. Gauging Bancroft's Role -- t8. In for the Long Haul, 1778- 1783 -- t9. Arthur Lee: Spy Catcher? Benjamin Franklin: Traitor? Edward Bancroft: Murderer? -- t10. In America, 1783- 1784 -- t11. Return to Normalcy -- tEpilogue -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA man of as many names as motives, Edward Bancroft is a singular figure in the history of Revolutionary America. Born in Massachusetts in 1745, Bancroft moved to England as a young man in the 1760s and began building a respectable résumé as both a scientist and a man of letters. In recognition of his works in natural history, Bancroft was unanimously elected to the Royal Society, and while working to secure French aid for the American Revolution, he became a close associate of such luminaries as Benjamin Franklin, Silas Deane, and John Adams. Though lauded in his time as a staunch American patriot, when the British diplomatic archives were opened in the late nineteenth century, it was revealed that Bancroft led a secret life as a British agent acting against French and American interests.In this book, the first complete biography of Bancroft, historian Thomas J. Schaeper reveals the full extent of the agent's deception during the crucial years of the American Revolution. Operating under aliases, working in ciphers, and leaving coded messages in the trees of Paris's Tuileries Gardens, Bancroft filtered information from unsuspecting figures including Franklin and Deane back to his contacts in Britain, navigating a complicated web of political allegiances. Through Schaeper's keen analysis of Bancroft's correspondence and diplomatic records, this biography reveals whether Bancroft should ultimately be considered a traitor to America or a patriot to Britain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300171716423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300171716.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles